# Onshape FeatureScript

**FeatureScript** is Onshape's strongly-typed, side-effect-controlled scripting
language for parametric CAD. A **custom feature** is written in a **Feature Studio**
element (a `.fs` tab in a document) and, once published, appears in the Part Studio
feature toolbar next to the built-in extrude/fillet/etc. — its dialog is generated
from the script's `precondition` block. The same language also runs **ad hoc**
against a model via the `/featurescript` evaluate endpoint, the headless
"measure / query geometry" path.

Two distinct surfaces, both here: the **language** (what you write in a `.fs`) and
the **REST endpoints** (how a Feature Studio and the eval path are reached). Worked
example throughout: `curvedKeyboardMatrix.fs` (the "Curved keyboard matrix" feature
in kb2).

## Model

- A **Feature Studio** is just another `eid` (element/tab) under a `did/wid`, like a
  Part Studio or Assembly (see @onshape/partstudios). Reads accept the `/{wvm}/`
  path family (`/w/` workspace, `/v/` version, `/m/` microversion); the text update
  POST must target a workspace `/w/`. Its content is the **source text** of one or
  more custom features plus helper functions/constants.
- A published custom feature is **inserted into a Part Studio** as a `BTMFeature`
  (`btType: BTMFeature-134`) in that studio's feature tree — the same node type the
  built-in features use. Its `parameters` array is keyed by the `definition.<field>`
  names declared in the precondition; defer the full insert/parameter envelope to
  @onshape/features (POST `…/features`).
- A custom feature references its source studio by a version-pinned
  `featureType`/import — the toolbar entry is the published studio's feature spec
  (see `featurespecs` below).

## Language essentials

Grounded in `curvedKeyboardMatrix.fs`.

**Header.** Every studio opens with a version pragma + imports. The version pins the
std library; ops/types resolve against it.

```fs
FeatureScript 3008;
import(path : "onshape/std/geometry.fs", version : "3008.0");
```

`onshape/std/geometry.fs` re-exports the common surface (`opExtrude`, `Query`,
`vector`, units…); other std modules exist (`onshape/std/*.fs`).

**Feature definition.** A custom feature is a `defineFeature` bound to an exported
`const`, tagged by an `annotation` map that names the toolbar entry:

```fs
annotation { "Feature Type Name" : "Curved keyboard matrix" }
export const curvedKeyboardMatrix = defineFeature(function(context is Context, id is Id, definition is map)
    precondition { ... }
    { ...body... });
```

- `context is Context` — the live geometry/regeneration state the body mutates.
- `id is Id` — a unique id the feature owns; every op gets a sub-id derived from it
  (`id + "delCol"`, `id + ("capBox" ~ i)`), which is how features stay re-runnable
  and topology IDs stay deterministic.
- `definition is map` — the dialog values, one key per precondition input.

**Precondition = the dialog.** Each statement in `precondition` is a typed input;
the preceding `annotation` map supplies its UI (name, default, picker filter). The
field on the left of the type predicate is exactly the `definition.<field>` you read
in the body. Examples straight from the file:

```fs
annotation { "Name" : "Row curve radius (X)", "Default" : 180 * millimeter }
isLength(definition.radiusX, KEYBOARD_LENGTH_BOUNDS);

annotation { "Name" : "Switch cutout X", "Default" : 14 * millimeter }
isLength(definition.cutoutX, KEYBOARD_LENGTH_BOUNDS);

annotation { "Name" : "Show clearance boxes", "Default" : true }
definition.showClearance is boolean;

annotation { "Name" : "Block to cut (optional)", "Filter" : EntityType.BODY, "MaxNumberOfPicks" : 1 }
definition.block is Query;
```

Input predicates seen here: `isLength(field, bounds)`, `isAngle(field, bounds)`,
`isInteger(field, bounds)`, `field is boolean`, `field is Query` (a geometry picker —
`Filter`/`MaxNumberOfPicks` constrain selection), and `field is array` for a
**repeatable group** (with `"Item name"`/`"Item label template"`), each iteration
declaring its own nested inputs:

```fs
annotation { "Name" : "Per-key hinge angle", "Item name" : "key", "Item label template" : "Key #index" }
definition.keyAdjust is array;
for (var key in definition.keyAdjust)
{
    annotation { "Name" : "Key index" }
    isInteger(key.index, KEY_INDEX_BOUNDS);
    annotation { "Name" : "Hinge angle", "Default" : 0 * degree }
    isAngle(key.rotX, KEY_ANGLE_BOUNDS);
}
```

`*BoundSpec` constants give `[min, default, max]` per unit and are the legal range
of a numeric input:

```fs
const KEYBOARD_LENGTH_BOUNDS = { (millimeter) : [0.01, 19.05, 10000] } as LengthBoundSpec;
const KEY_INDEX_BOUNDS       = { (unitless)   : [0, 0, 18] } as IntegerBoundSpec;
```

**Units are part of the type.** Numbers carry dimension as `ValueWithUnits`; you
build them by multiplying a scalar by a unit symbol (`180 * millimeter`,
`0 * degree`, `vector(0,0,0) * meter`). Mixing dimensions is a type error, so
`radiusX` (a length) can never be confused with `rotX` (an angle). Available units
include `meter`/`millimeter` (length), `degree`/`radian` (angle), etc. A bare
scalar input uses `(unitless)`.

**Types** in play: `Context`, `Id`, `map`, `Query` (a *deferred* reference to
geometry — never resolved entities, resolved on demand), `array`, `boolean`,
`ValueWithUnits`. Selectors and results are `Query`/`map`, not concrete handles.

**Querying geometry.** A `Query` is a recipe for "which entities", evaluated late:

```fs
capBoxQ = append(capBoxQ, qCreatedBy(id + ("capBox" ~ i), EntityType.BODY));   // bodies this op made
...
if (size(evaluateQuery(context, definition.block)) > 0) { ... }                 // resolve -> array of entities
if (size(evaluateQuery(context, definition.templateBase)) > 0) { ... }
```

`qCreatedBy(opId, type)` selects what a given op produced; `evaluateQuery(context,
q)` resolves a query to a concrete array (its `size` is how you test "did the user
pick anything / did anything get made"). Other combinators: `qUnion([...])`,
`qSketchRegion(sketchId)`, `qNothing()` (the empty query). The `#field` form (e.g.
`#index` in the label template) interpolates a group item's field into UI strings.

**Building geometry — ops mutate `context`.** Every `op*` call takes
`(context, id, params-map)` and adds to the model:

```fs
var sk = newSketchOnPlane(context, id + ("keySketch" ~ i), { "sketchPlane" : keyPlane });
skRectangle(sk, "switchCutout", { "firstCorner" : ..., "secondCorner" : ... });
skSolve(sk);

opExtrude(context, id + ("capBox" ~ i), {
    "entities" : qSketchRegion(id + ("capSketch" ~ i)),
    "direction" : normal,
    "endBound" : BoundingType.BLIND,
    "endDepth" : definition.keycapHeight
});

opPattern(context, id + "placeParts", {
    "entities" : definition.seed,
    "transforms" : keyTransforms,      // an array of Transform
    "instanceNames" : keyNames
});

opBoolean(context, id + "keywellCut", {
    "tools" : qUnion(keywellQ), "targets" : definition.block,
    "operationType" : BooleanOperationType.SUBTRACTION
});
```

Also used in the file: `opDeleteBodies`, `setProperty` (e.g.
`PropertyType.APPEARANCE` → `color(r,g,b,a)`), transform helpers
(`toWorld`/`coordSystem`/`identityTransform`/`inverse`), measurements
(`evCollision`, `evMateConnector`), and error reporting
`throw regenError("…message…")` to fail regeneration with a user-visible message.
A built-in **variable** is set/read with `setVariable(context, id, name, value)` /
the `#var` access (the `#` sigil reads a feature variable / interpolates a group
field); this file leans on plain local `var`s and arrays instead.

> Custom features may only call **`op*`/`ev*`/`sk*`** through `context`; arbitrary
> side effects aren't allowed — the engine guarantees deterministic, replayable
> regeneration. That's also why every op is keyed by a sub-id of `id`.

## Endpoints

Feature Studio element endpoints (from the `featurestudios` slice):

| METHOD path | purpose |
|---|---|
| `POST /featurestudios/d/{did}/w/{wid}` | create a new Feature Studio tab; body `{name}` |
| `GET  /featurestudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}` | get the Feature Studio's source **text** |
| `POST /featurestudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}` | update the Feature Studio's source **text** |
| `GET  /featurestudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/featurespecs` | the feature specs (toolbar entries + their param specs) this studio publishes |

The evaluate / introspection endpoints live on the **Part Studio** (from the
`partstudios` slice):

| METHOD path | purpose |
|---|---|
| `POST /partstudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/featurescript` | run a FS snippet against the model, return its `result` |
| `GET  /partstudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/featurescriptrepresentation` | the studio's tree as FeatureScript source |
| `GET  /partstudios/d/{did}/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/featurespecs` | specs for the features available in this Part Studio |

Inserting a published custom feature into a Part Studio = POST a `BTMFeature` to
`…/partstudios/.../features` whose `parameters` carry the precondition fields — see
@onshape/features for the call envelope.

## Shapes

**Evaluate a snippet** — `POST …/e/{eid}/featurescript`. The body wraps the script
text and an optional `queries` map (named queries you reference from the script);
the response returns `result` (a serialized FeatureScript value, `BTFSValue-1888`),
plus `console` and `notices`:

```json
// request
{
  "script": "function (context is Context, queries) { return size(evaluateQuery(context, qEverything(EntityType.BODY))); }",
  "queries": [],
  "serializationVersion": "1.2.0"
}
```

```json
// response (trimmed)
{
  "result":  { "btType": "BTFSValue-1888", "...": "serialized return value" },
  "console": "",
  "notices": []
}
```

The `script` is a FeatureScript **function literal** `function(context is Context,
queries) { … }`; whatever it `return`s comes back serialized in `result`. Query
parameters declared in the `queries` body field are passed in as the second arg.
Optional query params: `configuration`, `rollbackBarIndex`, `linkDocumentId`,
`elementMicroversionId`.

**Feature specs** — `GET …/featurespecs` returns
`{ featureSpecs: [BTFeatureSpec-129], libraryVersion, sourceMicroversion, … }`; each
spec is one published feature (its type name + parameter spec, i.e. the precondition
rendered as data). This is how a client discovers a custom feature's parameters
before inserting it.

## Recipe

Read-only: evaluate a trivial script against kb2's Part Studio and assert the
returned body count. Basic auth per the shared brief (`access:secret` over HTTPS,
local testing only; production uses HMAC — @onshape/auth). **No writes** — this only
reads geometry back.

```bash
DID=378e93b0ad360aa043a0220b
WID=09273312fedee7bf3c3482ad
EID=a77918b06d5131918477a269
BASE=https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10

# count bodies in the Part Studio via a FeatureScript snippet
curl -sS -u "$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY" \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  -X POST "$BASE/partstudios/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID/featurescript" \
  -d '{
        "script": "function (context is Context, queries) { return size(evaluateQuery(context, qEverything(EntityType.BODY))); }",
        "queries": [],
        "serializationVersion": "1.2.0"
      }' | tee /tmp/fs_eval.json
```

Verify — the call succeeded and `result` carries a non-negative integer body count
(a count, never an error notice):

```bash
python3 - <<'PY'
import json
d = json.load(open("/tmp/fs_eval.json"))
assert not d.get("notices"), f"FS notices: {d['notices']}"
res = d["result"]
# BTFSValue wraps the number; dig for the numeric payload
val = res.get("value", res.get("message", res))
n = int(val) if isinstance(val, (int, float, str)) and str(val).lstrip("-").isdigit() else None
print("result:", res)
assert n is not None and n >= 0, f"expected an integer body count, got {res!r}"
print("OK body count =", n)
PY
```

> The exact nesting of the number inside `BTFSValue-1888` is per spec — print
> `result` once and read the real key before hard-asserting on a path. If the script
> errors, the call still returns 200 with the message in `notices`/`console`, not an
> HTTP error — always check `notices` first. Swap `qEverything(EntityType.BODY)` for
> any measurement to read geometry headlessly (the API "measure" path).

## See also

- @onshape/features — insert a published custom feature as a `BTMFeature`; the
  parameter envelope that mirrors the precondition.
- @onshape/partstudios — the Part Studio this evaluates against; the feature tree.
- @onshape/variables — feature variables (`setVariable`/`#var`) surfaced as document
  variables.
- @onshape/configurations — configured inputs that drive a custom feature's
  parameters across variants.
- @onshape/auth — Basic vs HMAC signing for the calls above.
- @onshape/playwright — UI fallback: author/edit a Feature Studio in the browser
  when the API can't express it.
